Hola! It’s @simplyfloritza again! Today I’m coming with our last recipe in the series, soup! Sofrito is an excellent soup base and an easy way to add flavor to your broth.  I love a good soup and tend to make this often because it is also a great way to get your veggies! 
.
.
.
Ingredients: 
Two frozen sofrito pods 
1/2 lb. seasoned beef meatballs 
Olive oil 
1.5 cups chicken stock 
1.5 cups water 
Choice of veggies (carrots, celery, onions, garlic, potatoes)
Choice of vegetable noodles (I use one spiraled zucchini) 
Salt and pepper to taste 
.
.
Directions:
1. In a pot, sauté onions in olive oil. 
2. Add beef meatballs and cook until slightly browned
3. Add garlic and sofrito pod and Mix well, follow by adding remaining veggies and stir. 
4. Add chicken stock and water and allow to simmer 
5. Follow with a second sofrito pod and salt and pepper to taste. 
6. Add zucchini noodles and allow to simmer for 5 min. 
7. Serve hot. 
.
.
.
Remember to find the sofrito recipe, go to @simplyfloritza and click the highlight titled “sofrito”. You can also find that and so many other recipes by checking out my YouTube channel Simplyfloritza! 
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

👋 Hey friends! We’re Abe and Isaac (@abelopez), husbands and creators. We run a company called Lightward, because that’s what we know: to move in the direction that feels like light. We were here last February, too—thanks for having us back! 😄

OUR THEME THIS WEEK: Where you are is REAL and we can WORK with that, to good-feeling, positive ends. Begin where you are, and believe you can make something good with what you have. 💪

** Hey I’m Abe! I’ve been sharing my health story at #abeminus100. Growing up with mostly processed/fast food and zero veggies, I never thought about what food could really do for me. In my late 20s, after a few health scares, I realized I just wanted to feel GOOD in my body. And then I found W30! It’s been a huge part of this turnaround, giving me space to fully reset and rebuild my relationship to food, losing the sugar/fries addictions, learning to love my body more and more, and giving me a new appreciation for food as something that makes my life better every day.

Today, I’m down 65lbs, and #abeminus100 has become so much more than weight loss for me. It’s about loving my body in all the ways that I can, and celebrating him every day. Every day in this beautiful body of mine is a gift.

** I’m Isaac! My whole deal is the journey to *understand*, and to build with the things I’m learning to understand. I grew up on a potato farm in the woods of northern Wisconsin, as the eldest of five. School took me to Chicago, where I spent a bunch of years beginning to seriously unfold. And I met Abe exactly seven years ago, as I write this on April 4. 🥰 Happy anniversary, darling.

My health story is a constant conversation with my body. I have strong trust for what my gut tells me, for what my heart can hear, and for what my mind can discern. All of this shows up in how I run Lightward, and it shows up in how I cook. 😄 W30 was when I started to understand food, from the salt-fat-acid-heat side of things to the ingredients themselves. (Have you ever just stared at a vegetable for five minutes? TRY IT.) I love living and exploring, and this takeover with Abe is a part of that. 🙃

** Love y’all! Pumped for this week—thanks for being here.

If you head to stories right now you can still catch my 4 tips on “How to Make a Whole30 Work for You.” And as a gift I will leave you with these last two bonus tips:
1) Not one Whole30 is the same. Your W30 will look different than mine and that’s OK. I just wanted to let you know you have a place here, whatever knowledge you wanna take away from the Whole30 program there will always be room for you at the table here.
2) Show yourself grace and enjoy the journey. It’s not overnight, it might not be after 30 days but I hope you now have the tools to cultivate a food freedom fit for YOU.
•
Whole30 was an awakening for me, a place to call home when I needed refuge. It helped me find myself again and enlightened me to the power of food. I wish nothing more than for you to discover your own joy in the pursuit of this messy and unpredictable journey of self-discovery and wellness. ♥️✨

✨UKOY (Filipino Fritters)✨
Coach Alexis @asideofalexis with my last coaching tip:
Let’s talk shallow fry, nut butters, nuts and dried fruit. All Whole30 compatible but if these types of  foods or snacks trigger your “food with no breaks” or your sugar dragon, proceed with caution and some self-awareness. Check in with yourself, have that internal dialogue. This kind of self reflection is vital when it comes to cultivating a food freedom specific to you and your individual needs.
•
Now we’ve come full circle to the first recipe I shared. Remember that Crispy Sweet Potato Nest from last week? Its origin actually comes from my Tita’s (aunt) Ukoy recipe. Ukoy (pronounced ooh-coy) is a Filipino root vegetable fritter with tiny shrimp. Any root vegetable works but my Tita keeps hers simple with just shredded carrots.

UKOY (ooh-coy)
@asideofalexis
Serves 6-7
•
Ingredients:
2 bags of shredded carrots
1 cup frozen baby/tiny shrimp, roughly chopped (excess water removed)
3-4 green onion stalks, thinly sliced 
Enough arrowroot powder to coat ingredients evenly. 
•
Instructions:

REMOVE frozen bay shrimp from the freezer and set aside for about 10 min.
RINSE under cold water and remove excess water with a paper towel or cheese cloth. CHOP shrimp, small dice.
COMBINE shredded carrots, shrimp, chopped scallions.
ADD 2-3 tbsp. arrowroot powder or until everything is evenly coated. Toss together.
PREHEAT large skillet with 1/4”-1/2” of avocado oil. Not too much, just a shallow fry.
ADD a small handful of your shrimp-carrot mixture and gently place in the hot oil.
*You can use tongs instead of your hands if hot oil make you nervous.
FRY on med.-high heat. Adjust burner if they brown too quickly. Fry until edges start to crisp and fritter is more formed.
FLIP and fry another few minutes.
*You can turn the Ukoy occasionally to crisp evenly.
DRAIN on paper towel or cooling rack and immediately sprinkle with sea salt.
•
Dipping Sauce aka sukang sawsawan:
1/3 cup W30 compatible vinegar
1 garlic clove, pressed
1 sliced serrano or 2-3 labuyo peppers
Cracked pepper and pinch of sea salt

✨CHICKEN ADOBO✨ 
Whole30 coach Alexis @sideofalexis here on my last day with you but first, growing up Sundays were “family days” and Sunday supper was mandatory no matter what everybody’s social calendars were. So I thought we could do the same today! I’ve got two Filipino recipes for you that I’m sure will be a hit on your table too.

Chicken/Pork Adobo is a staple in any Filipino household. In the video tutorial the marinade ratios stated are for smaller batches of Adobo but the ratio is still the same for larger batches like the recipe below. 2:1 coconut aminos to vinegar.
Could you make this in the IP or slow cooker? Yes you absolutely can. But will it be just as tasty as Lola‘s (grandma)? I’ll let you be the judge but for now let’s keep it old school, stovetop style...
•
CHICKEN ADOBO 
@asideofalexis
Serves 4-6

Ingredients:

3-4 lbs m. bone-in chicken, dark and breast
2 cups coconut aminos
1/2 cup of apple cider vinegar
1/2 cup rice vinegar 
palm full peppercorns
whole head of cracked garlic cloves
4 bay leaves.

Instructions:

PLACE chicken in pot. Add all ingredients.
MARINATE chicken all day or overnight.
REMOVE chicken from the fridge when ready to eat. 
SEAR marinated chicken in a large wok or shallow pot with 2 tbsp. avocado oil.
BROWN each piece of chicken until it has a nice color on them and set aside.
ADD all the chicken and marinade back into wok. The marinade will eventually reduce and cook off.
COVER and braise on medium-low. for  40ish min.
*tip* Do not stir/touch the chicken and marinade for the first 10-15 min. Let the vinegar cook off and the sauce reduce.
TURN chicken over halfway through to cook evenly letting the chicken get nice and tender falling off the bone. 

*You can do this in the slow cooker on high 4 hrs or in the IP 1-2 hrs but the sauce won’t reduce or be as thick as it would stovetop.
•
Crispy Umami Broccolirice
Ingredients:
1 bag of pearled broccoli/broccoli rice
1 tbsp @nomnompaleo’s magic mushroom powder
Enough olive oil to lightly coat evenly.

Instructions:
Toss ingredients together on a sheet pan and roast 425-450° for 20-25 min or until airy, light and crispy. Ovens vary.

✨ZOODLE PRIMAVERA✨
Whole30 Coach Alexis here from @asideofalexis and let’s talk cravings! I conceptualized this dish one day when I had a craving for pasta primavera. Which I know must have been the sugar dragon talking because pasta isn’t even a part of my food freedom. But it happens. Sometimes the sugar dragon kicks in when you least expect it. So I reflected on my craving and instead of fighting it, I embraced it. I daydreamed about what I really wanted from this dish (yes, I daydream about food all day long):
1. Some thing fun to twirl and slurp
2. Yummy savory sausage
3. Fresh vegetables

ZOODLE PRIMAVERA
@asideofalexis
Serves 4-6

Ingredients:
3-4 boxes of frozen zoodles of 6 large zucchini
1 package of compatible sausages, sliced or diced
1 small container of mushroomed, sliced
1 onion
3-4 garlic cloves
1 bunch of bitter greens, coarsely chopped
@thenewprimal Citrus Herb seasoning
Parsley, garnish

Directions:
BROWN sausage in a large skillet with 1 tbsp. olive oil on med.-high heat.
SAUTÉ onion and garlic, about 2-4 min.
ADD mushrooms and citrus herb seasoning, sauté 2-3 min.
ADD Swiss chard or bitter greens and cook down until slightly wilted.
REMOVE from pan and garnish with fresh herbs.
PREP zoodles and serve with sausage primavera on top.
•
ZOODLES

Frozen zoodles:
Add frozen Zoodles directly into the pan with 1 tbsp olive oil and sauté on medium high, defrosting the Zoodles. Drain off excess water. When excess water is removed continue sautéing and season zoodles with citrus herb seasoning.

Fresh Zucchini:
Spiralize zucchini (saving the scraps for a soup or hash). Sauté on high heat cooking off any excess liquid from the zucchini. Season zoodles with citrus herb seasoning.
•
Song: “Call On Me” by Starley, Ryan Riback

What’s your favorite summer-y salad? 🥗 This week we have 3 salads that pair perfectly with our 3 most popular Made By Whole30 dressings.

Peek at our Stories to learn more about our Made By Whole30 dressings.

Today’s recipe: Grilled Steak and Peach Salad from THE WHOLE30 FRIENDS & FAMILY by @melissau. If you’re short on time, our Creamy Balsamic works perfectly with the savory steak and sweet peach flavors. *Recipe continues in comments.

GRILLED STEAK AND PEACH SALAD

For the Peach Vinaigrette
1 large ripe peach, pitted & coarsely chopped
2 cloves garlic, minced
1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
1/3 cup white wine vinegar
1 tsp coarse salt
1/2 tsp black pepper
1 tbsp Whole30-compatible coarse-grain Dijon mustard
1 tbsp coconut aminos

For the Steak
1/2 cup coconut aminos
1 tsp coarse salt
1 tsp black pepper
1 tsp garlic powder
2 lbs flank steak

For the Salad
4 large ripe peaches, pitted and quartered
2 tbsp avocado oil
3 5-ounce containers spinach and arugula salad blend
2 medium ripe avocados, halved, pitted, peeled, and sliced
4 slices Whole30-compatible bacon, crisp-cooked and crumbled
1 medium red onion, thinly sliced and rings separated
1/2 cup coarsely chopped pecans
 
MAKE the Peach Vinaigrette
In a blender or food processor, combine the peach, garlic, olive oil, vinegar, 1 teaspoon salt, pepper, mustard, & 1 tablespoon coconut aminos. Cover & blend or process until well combined. Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator until ready to serve.

MAKE the Salad
In a small bowl, combine the 1⁄2 cup coconut aminos, 1 teaspoon salt, pepper, & garlic powder. Place the steak in a large resealable plastic bag; add the marinade. Seal and turn to coat the steak. Marinate in the refrigerator, turning occasionally, at least 1 hour or up to overnight.

PREHEAT the grill to medium-high heat. Remove the steak from the marinade & discard the marinade. Arrange the steak on the grill rack. Grill, turning once halfway through, until cooked to desired doneness, 12 to 15 minutes for medium (145°F).

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty with another Cameroonian popular dish - Poisson Braise or roasted grilled fish. Cameroon is big on street food - from beignets/puff puff, to roasted corn and plum, to suya and roasted fish among many others. We typically serve it with a pepper sauce, fries, fried plantains (dodo) or miondo/bobolo (fermented cassava wrapped in banana leaves ). It's one of my favorite meals and recently became a Sunday routine for my hubby and I. We use various traditional spices like njangsang when making Poisson Braise but I've kept the spices simple here so that you can easily recreate it wherever you are. 

Servings: 3 

Ingredients
3 whole fish (usually tilapia or mackerel)
1/2 cup green seasoning (recipe posted 5 posts back)
1 tomato
1 tbsp smoked paprika
1/4 cup oil
1 scotch bonnet pepper, optional
1 tsp coconut aminos
1 tsp fish sauce
1 tsp salt or taste

Instructions
BLEND all the ingredients from green seasoning through to scotch bonnet pepper till smooth.
CLEAN fish then dry with a paper towel to remove as much moisture as possible. Make 3-5 diagonal slits in the fish for better penetration of spices. Season fish with salt, fish sauce and coconut aminos then brush on 2 tablespoon of spice blend over the fish. 
LINE a baking tray with aluminum, place a baking rack over the tray and place the fish on the rack. Bake at 400F for 30mins. If you have a convection oven then convect broil for 20-25mins at 400F 
MEANWHILE, add 2 tablespoons of oil, salt, fish sauce and coconut aminos to the remaining blend mix and cook on the stove or in the microwave for 5-7mins. 
SERVE fish with cooked blend and a side of fried plantains/fries 

Blog post: https://wellandtasty.com/poisson-braise-cameroonian-whole-grilled-fish/

#grilledfish #wholefish #poissonbraisé #whole30 #whole30recipes

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty. TGIF! Sharing this Cameroonian one pot dish that is perfect for mealprep. It is called Hot Pot Potatoes and is one of those dishes that only gets better with each day so great for meal prep. Those who watch my YouTube videos know I'm obsessed with adding greens and vegetables wherever I can. In this recipe I add swiss chard for a boost of fiber. I hope you enjoy it 

Serves 8
Ingredients
2.5 lbs Chicken bone-in, skin-on
1 tsp smoked paprika
1 tsp herb de provence
1 tsp garlic powder
1 tsp onion powder
1 large onion diced
3 tomatoes diced
1 tbsp green seasoning (recipe 4 posts back) 
3 russett potatoes chopped
1 tsp coconut aminos
1 tsp fish sauce
2 cups chicken broth
2 large carrots chopped
1 cup green beans chopped
2 cups swiss chard chopped
Salt and pepper
1 scotch bonnet pepper optional

Instructions
DRIZZLE 2 tbsp of oil over chicken. ADD dry rub spices - 1 tsp each of smoked paprika, herb de provence, garlic and onion powder, salt and pepper. Mix well to coat chicken. Then brown the chicken in hot pan, remove and set aside 
In the same pan, add onion and cook till translucent. 
ADD tomatoes, green seasoning and spices (remaining smoked paprika, garlic & onion powder), fish sauce and coconut aminos, salt and pepper to taste. Cook 7-10mins. Add 1/4c water or stock to prevent tomatoes from burning if needed. 
ADD chopped potatoes. Return and nestle chicken back into the pot. Add 2 cups of chicken broth and cook 10mins
MEANWHILE cover carrots and string beans in water and place in the microwave to steam 5mins. ADD to pot along with chopped swiss chard. Cook another 5mins then serve and enjoy! 

Recipe blog post: https://wellandtasty.com/hot-pot-potatoes/

#whole30 #africanfood #cameroonianfood #hotpot #potatoes

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty with a one pot cauliflower jollof rice recipe. Jollof rice is a staple in most West African countries and for the last couple of years we've heard the "wars" between Nigeria and Ghana to decide which country has the best jollof rice. The jury is still out but in my humble opinion, Senegal wears that crown - after all they are the originators of jollof rice. Of course a close second is Cameroon but some will say I'm biased😜. This cauliflower jollof rice is loaded with vegetables, and comes together in a West African seasoned tomato stew. Skip the extra carbs and serve this with some grilled protein. Served mine with some bronzino fillets. 

Servings: 4
Ingredients
1 head of cauliflower fresh, chopped
2 tbsp avocado oil
1 large onion chopped
2 tomatoes chopped
1 tbsp green seasoning (see recipe 2posts back)
1 tsp curry powder
1 tsp tomato paste
1 bay leaf
1/2 cup chicken/vegetable broth
1 bell pepper or 1/2 red, 1/2 green chopped
1 tsp fish sauce
1 tsp coconut aminos

Instructions:
Prep the Cauliflower. You can use a food processor. If no food processor slice and coarsely chop the florets with a knife. 

Hit 2 tablespoons of oil in a large non stick skillet. Add onions and saute till translucent

Add tomatoes, tomato paste, green seasoning, curry powder, bay leaf. Cook down until tomatoes are sweet and no longer tart. 7 minutes. 

Add stock, cauliflower rice, chopped bell peppers, fish sauce and coconut aminos. Stir together and cook 7-10mins until cauliflower rice is cooked through. *See recipe notes. 

Serve and enjoy! I like a grilled protein like fish or chicken on the side

Recipe Notes
*I recommend fresh cauliflower. Frozen can have too much moisture and make your end results mushy

** When cooking the cauliflower rice, spread it out in a flat thin layer, cook 2 mins then stir. Repeat this process for 7-10mins until rice is cooked through. This helps toast the cauliflower rice to develop rich flavor and color

Full recipe: https://wellandtasty.com/cauliflower-jollof-rice/

#cauliflower #cauliflowerrice #jollofrice #whole30 #whole30recipes

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty with a sauteed spinach and cabbage dish that is sure to prevent you from ever making the same old boring spinach recipe again. In my job as a diabetes educator, and working with many low income families, it is my responsibility to introduce budget friendly ways to encourage more fiber in my clients' diets. My mother introduced me to this recipe a while back and it has become a staple in my kitchen and in my conversations with clients. Hope you give it a try. 

Ingredients
24 oz Chopped frozen spinach
1/2 Head of cabbage, sliced thin
5 cloves garlic, sliced thin
1 teaspoon Fish sauce**
1 teaspoon coconut aminos**
Pinch of red pepper flakes
Salt & Pepper
1 tablespoon avocado oil

Instructions
Run cold water over your frozen spinach to thaw. Then squeeze out the excess water. Season the spinach with salt, pepper fish sauce and coconut aminos then set aside

In a saucepan hit up your oil. Sauté and brown garlic then remove to the side

Add the spinach to the saucepan and saute at least 5 minutes until it is heated through. Then add cabbage and stir to blend well. Season with salt, pepper and a few more dashes of fish sauce as needed. Sauté another 3-5mins.

Top with browned garlic and crushed red pepper flakes. Enjoy

Full recipe on www.wellandtasty.com and on Youtube

Recipe Notes
**A combo of fish sauce and coconut aminos is used instead of Maggi/Bouillon cubes for that same umami flavor 
***You can squeeze over some lemon to finish 

#africanfood #sauteedspinach #cabbage #spinach #whole30

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty with a Cameroonian wonder dish called Poulet DG. “Poulet” is the french word for chicken and “DG – Directeur Generale” would translate into “General Director” or loosely “Managing Director.” One could then infer that this chicken dish is one reserved for the very elite to be enjoyed on special occasions. However, these days anyone can enjoy it :). Typically a whole chicken is used and both the chicken and plantains are fried. I have made the recipe more whole30 compatible without losing any of the flavor. 

Ingredients
For the chicken:
2.5 lbs chicken wings
1 Tbsp salt
1 Tsp black pepper
1 Tsp each onion powder, cumin, curry powder, red pepper flakes 
1 Tablespoon each, smoked paprika, herbe de Provence 

For the plantains:
6 plantains
Oil for frying

For the tomato sauce:
1 large onion chopped
1/2 cup green seasoning blend (see recipe) optional
2 Tbsp tomato paste
4 fresh tomatoes chopped
1.5cup chicken stock divided
1 large carrot chopped into matchstick
1/4 each green, red and yellow bell pepper
1 scotch bonnet pepper/habenero pepper
1/2 tablespoon fish sauce
1 tablespoon coconut aminos

Instructions
For the chicken:
Mix all spices together in a small bowl then reserve 1/3 of the blend and set aside. Season chicken with remaining spice blend. Bake at 400 F till brown and crispy flipping a couple times 30-40mins

For the plantains:
Cut the plantains into small discs and fry.

For the tomato sauce:
Heat up 1 tablespoon oil. Add chopped onions and cook till translucent. Add green seasoning, tomato paste, diced tomatoes, scotch bonnet and reserved 1/3 spice blend 
Cook tomatoes 10-15mins until vibrant in color and not tart. May add a little water/chicken stock 1/4c at a time to prevent tomatoes from drying up or burning 
Add chopped carrots, baked chicken and its juices, chicken stock and cook another 10mins
Add chopped bell peppers and fried plantains. Toss well to combine and cook another 3 minutes. Serve and enjoy. 

Recipe Notes
*Select firm yellow plantains. Avoid blackened plantains as these would be too sift
*A combo of fish sauce + coconut aminos is used instead of Maggi for umani.

Hi! Tina here from @wellandtasty with my first recipe. When it comes to cooking, I'm very intuitive and terrible at following recipes. I like recipes that are forgiving, that are flexible and you can easily modify. This green seasoning blend is a game changer in the kitchen and the best part is that it is totally customizable and you don't need to measure. 

It can be used to season meats, fish, stews and just about anything you can imagine. While the aromatics of ginger, garlic and onions are a must, you can customize the herbs with your faves. And if you don't like something (say cilantro) then leave it out - you're the boss. This adds a punch of flavor to any dish being cooked and I guarantee you will find a jar of some version of it in any Cameroonian’s fridge. You'll also find similar blends in some parts of the Caribbean often referred to as sofrito or epis. So you see we are all connected through food!

Green Seasoning:
Ingredients:
1 large onion, chopped 
1/4 cup ginger, roughly chopped
3 scallions, chopped
1 head of garlic
1/2 cup basil
1/4 cup cilantro
1 cup parsley
2 sprigs of rosemary
2 tbsps of thyme
1/2cup water 

Instructions:
Roughly chop all the aromatics and herbs. It will all be dumped into the blender so a rough chop is fine

Transfer all your chopped ingredients to your blender. Add water and blend till smooth for about 2-3mins. 

Store your blend in a glass container, like a mason jar and you are good to go! It's ready to be used as a marinade for your protein or as a seasoning in your stews. It will last in your fridge for 2-3weeks at least and longer if you blend with oil instead of water

Watch the recipe in stories or check out my YouTube channel for how to video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1c02apdCH58 

#greenseasoning #epis #sofrito

Hi Whole30recipes family! My name is Tina from @wellandtasty. I am a Cameroonian gal from West Africa living in NYC with my husband. This is my first time here and I am excited to spend the week with you. 

I am a nurse and work full time as a certified diabetes care and education specialist, working with folks to help reverse diabetes. I am passionate about chronic disease management through food because I believe food can be our most powerful medicine. 

As an African immigrant living in NYC, the food I grew up eating is different from that which I see in most cookbooks or which the typical health professional advices. But the food we eat is part of our identity and culture and so it plays a huge role in my conversations with clients. In appreciating their food I can better understand them and have greater impact on the results we can achieve together.  I did my first whole30 in 2014 and since discovering this community I have been exposed to so many cultures and to learning how to make food work for me and those I love. My approach to nutrition and wellness is one that is easy and sustainable and borrows from the world around me. 

This week I’ll share simple, tasty recipes from Cameroon and hope you will follow along, as well as join my community on @wellandtasty and Youtube. But enough about me for now as I’d love to hear more about YOU. Where are you from and what are you looking to learn/gain on your whole30 journey? Thank you for bringing me into your space 🙏🏾

How are you keeping it cool this weekend? We’re prepping this no-cook Ahi Mango Salad from @cookbycolor. 🐟🥭🥒🧅🌶🥬 Check the Story for more no-cook recipe ideas.

INGREDIENTS

1 pound of sashimi grade ahi, chopped into small cubes
1-2 mangos, chopped into small cubes (depending on how big they are, and how sweet you like the poke)
1/2 cup Persian or English cucumbers - with the seeds removed, small dice
1/4 cup sliced sweet onion, optional
1-2 Serrano or jalapeno peppers, seeded and minced (depending how hot they are)
3 cups of mixed greens

For the Dressing

1/3 cup coconut aminos
1 tsp fish sauce
1 tsp sesame oil
3 green onions - white parts, finely chopped
1 small clove of garlic, minced
1/2" knob of ginger, minced or grated

Optional, but very encouraged garnish ideas:

1 Tbsp sesame seeds
1 Pinch of red chili flakes
2 tsp furikake (optional garnish made of sea salt, seaweed, sesame seeds)
1-2 tbsp macadamia nuts, chopped
Avocado, sliced
Sea salt to taste
Seaweed sheets for picking up the fish

INSTRUCTIONS

CUT the ahi into 3/4 inch cubes, against the grain. *Often times there is white streaks in the fish which is connective tissue and very chewy. When selecting your tuna keep this in mind.

ADD the ahi and the mango, cucumber, onion, serrano peppers to a large bowl

WHISK together the dressing ingredients

FOLD the dressing into the ahi mixture gently

POUR the ahi mixture over a bed of mixed greens

ADD garnishes to your preferences

Watermelon Refresher
INGREDIENTS
1 packet of LMNT Raw Electrolyte Drink Mix
1 cup of watermelon juice (or blended watermelon)
3 cups of water
Juice of 1 lime (about ¼ cup of juice)

GARNISH:
Fresh mint leaves
1-2 lime slices per glass

INSTRUCTIONS
POUR the watermelon juice, lime juice and water into a large pitcher

ADD LMNT Raw Electrolyte Drink Mix

MIX together well

MUDDLE a few mint leaves in a glass

ADD ice 

POUR LMNT watermelon refresher over ice

GARNISH with lime slices

SIP and enjoy staying hydrated!

What’s your favorite variety of protein salad? Do you prefer chicken, tuna, egg, or shrimp? 🐓🐟🥚🦐

Protein salads are a fantastic summer meal … light and cool and refreshing in hot weather, and requiring minimal or no cook time. We recommend this recipe for Sonoma Chicken Salad from @thisafricancooks.

Take it to the next picnic or make a big batch to keep in the fridge for quick meals. Serve with crisp lettuce cups or fresh veggies for a tasty, nourishing summer meal.

INGREDIENTS
4 medium sized boneless skinless chicken breast
2 cups chopped grapes
5 sticks celery finely chopped
1.5 tsp sea salt
1 whole chopped red onion
1 cup whole30 compliant mayo or more per preference
1 whole avocado chopped
10 whole dates finely chooped
1/2 cup chopped pecans
1 tsp black pepper
2 tsp apple cider vinegar
1 tsp smoked paprika or regular paprika
1 tbsp dried parsley you can use fresh parsley

INSTRUCTIONS
PLACE chicken breasts in a large pot and cover with water, add salt. Bring to a boil, until chicken is cooked fully. Remove from heat, and allow to cool. Once cooled, chop chicken into small bite-sized pieces or shred chicken.

ADD chicken to a large mixing bowl, then add the rest of the ingredients, except for the pecan. Mix well to combine, then transfer to a fridge safe bowl with a tight lid, top with pecans and extra parsley. Cover and refridgerate for about 1-2 hrs. Chicken salad is always better cold, and even better the next day. Serves 6-8. Refrigerate up to 4 days.
